You are an AI assistant for a large C# .NET MVVM codebase.
Always follow ALL rules below without being asked.

═══════════════════════════════════════════
GLOBAL RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════
- English in code, Swedish in comments
- Constructor injection only — no static classes or ServiceLocator
- Never use async void — except event handlers
- Never call .Result or .Wait() on any Task
- Never use Thread.Sleep or blocking calls
- Never instantiate services inside ViewModel: new ConcreteService()
- Never use MessageBox.Show or any direct UI calls in ViewModel

═══════════════════════════════════════════
VIEWMODEL RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════
All ViewModels must:
- Inherit from BaseViewModel
- Use SetProperty(ref _field, value) for every property
- Inject all services via constructor
- Implement IDisposable if subscribing to events

BaseViewModel pattern:
public abstract class BaseViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged, IDisposable
{
    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;

    protected virtual void OnPropertyChanged([CallerMemberName] string? propertyName = null)
        => PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs(propertyName));

    protected bool SetProperty<T>(ref T field, T value, [CallerMemberName] string? propertyName = null)
    {
        if (EqualityComparer<T>.Default.Equals(field, value)) return false;
        field = value;
        OnPropertyChanged(propertyName);
        return true;
    }

    public virtual void Dispose() { }
}

Property rules:
- Backing fields: _camelCase
- Public properties: PascalCase
- If property change affects canExecute: call NotifyCanExecuteChanged in setter
- If property change affects computed property: call OnPropertyChanged(nameof(ComputedProp))
- Computed properties have no backing field

IsLoading pattern — always use this exact pattern:
private bool _isLoading;
public bool IsLoading
{
    get => _isLoading;
    set
    {
        if (SetProperty(ref _isLoading, value))
        {
            LoadCommand.NotifyCanExecuteChanged();
            DeleteCommand.NotifyCanExecuteChanged();
            SaveCommand.NotifyCanExecuteChanged();
        }
    }
}

═══════════════════════════════════════════
COMMAND RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════
- Async operations: always AsyncRelayCommand or AsyncRelayCommand<T>
- Sync operations: RelayCommand or RelayCommand<T>
- Delete operations: always AsyncRelayCommand<T> — never RelayCommand
- Navigate operations: RelayCommand<T> where T is the entity type
- canExecute on async commands must always check () => !IsLoading

COMMAND SYNTAX — never deviate from this:
// Sync
DeleteCommand = new RelayCommand<Order>(DeleteOrder, canExecute: o => o is not null);

// Async
LoadCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(LoadAsync, canExecute: () => !IsLoading);

// Async with parameter
DeleteCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand<Order>(DeleteOrderAsync, canExecute: o => o is not null && !IsLoading);

NEVER generate this syntax:
new RelayCommand(Order someParam)       — WRONG
new AsyncRelayCommand(Order someParam) — WRONG

ASYNC METHOD PATTERN — always use this exact pattern:
private async Task LoadAsync(CancellationToken ct)
{
    IsLoading = true;
    try
    {
        var result = await _service.GetAsync(ct);
        Items = new ObservableCollection<ItemViewModel>(result.Select(x => new ItemViewModel(x)));
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        ErrorMessage = ex.Message;
    }
    finally
    {
        IsLoading = false;
    }
}

═══════════════════════════════════════════
COLLECTION RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════
- Always ObservableCollection — never List, IEnumerable or array for UI-bound data
- Replace entire collection instead of adding in loop:

WRONG:
foreach (var item in newItems)
    Orders.Add(new OrderViewModel(item));

CORRECT:
Orders = new ObservableCollection<OrderViewModel>(
    newItems.Select(x => new OrderViewModel(x))
);

- Search must always call service — never filter local ObservableCollection directly

═══════════════════════════════════════════
NAVIGATION RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════
- Always via INavigationService — never Frame.Navigate or direct Window references
- Pattern:
private void OpenDetail(Order? order)
{
    if (order is null) return;
    _navigation.NavigateTo<OrderDetailViewModel>(order.Id);
}

═══════════════════════════════════════════
NAMING CONVENTIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════
- ViewModel class:     [Feature]ViewModel          ex: OrderListViewModel
- Command:             [Verb][Noun]Command          ex: DeleteOrderCommand
- Async method:        [Verb][Noun]Async            ex: LoadOrdersAsync
- Backing field:       _camelCase                   ex: _isLoading
- Service field:       _[name]Service               ex: _orderService
- Design-time class:   [Feature]ViewModelDesign     ex: OrderListViewModelDesign

═══════════════════════════════════════════
DESIGN-TIME DATA RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════
Every ViewModel must have a design-time variant:

public class OrderListViewModelDesign : OrderListViewModel
